Tomb of Elizabeth I and Mary I at Westminster Abbey. This striking marble monument was erected by James I in the north aisle of Henry VII’s chapel. Elizabeth was originally buried in the vault of her grandfather King Henry VII, but a few years after her death she was moved to a vault below her new monument.
The crown, the cross on the orb, the sceptre, and the railing around the tomb are modern replacements.

A huge thank you to @kathrynholeman for this beautiful gift! I feel so blessed to have such thoughtful and supportive friends.
I’m also immensely thankful for everyone who’s taken the time to read and review my new book. The initial feedback has been very moving and encouraging. Here’s one recent review.
 
“Anne Boleyn is one of my favourite historical figures and I've read many books about her, but Natalie Grueninger's ‘The Final Year of Anne Boleyn’ really stood out to me. It was an excellent study of this remarkable woman's final year and of the events which led to her dramatic fall.

The book was both extremely well researched and accessible to read. The writing was always focused on the subject, and the events were recounted in a very clear, objective way. The second half was especially gripping: even if I knew what was going to happen, I couldn't put the book down.

I also appreciated how respectful the author was towards Anne, and how she really tried to bring her back to life and to give her justice. She managed to paint a very human and sympathetic portrayal of this formidable woman.

Lastly, I also really liked the appendix which contains the list of Anne's charges, and how Grueninger disputed them by pointing out that in most of these dates Anne was pregnant or in another place altogether.

Highly recommended.
 
~ Elena Vivenzi”

The Castel Sant’Angelo in Rome is home to some extraordinary 16th-century frescoes, friezes and gilt ceilings.
Hadrian, the Roman emperor, commissioned its construction in the first century AD as a mausoleum to house his remains and those of his descendants. 
Over the centuries, it was transformed into a fortress and subsequently a magnificent papal residence.
The apartments of Pope Paul III are a definite highlight, as are 360-degree views of Rome from the castle roof.

Some pics from my visit to Lyon Cathedral in France, home to, among other things, an ornate 17th-century astronomical clock.

Bourges Cathedral is home to these exquisite 15th-century sculptures of Duke Jean de Berry and his wife Jeanne de Boulogne. They were made by Jean de Cambrai in about 1403. The heads and hands were restored in the 19th century as they were damaged during the Revolution.

Today has been an absolutely amazing day! It started with a visit to the stunning Château de Chenonceau. During the 16th century it was home to a number of prominent women, including Diane de Poitiers and Catherine de’ Medici. 
I then followed in the footsteps of a young Anne Boleyn at the Château d'Amboise and ended the day with a visit to Le Château du Clos Lucé. Louise of Savoy lived there for a time with her two young children, the future King Francis I and Margaret of Navarre, but it’s perhaps best known as the home of Leonardo da Vinci, who lived and worked there for the last three years of his life, from 1516-1519. 
The accompanying pics were all taken at Chenonceau. I’ll share more very soon!

Today I visited and fell utterly in love with the beautiful Château Royal de Blois! It was a favourite residence of the French monarchs in the 16th century, including of Francis I and Queen Claude. 
I have so many pics and videos to share, but let’s begin with a selection taken on the first floor of the Francis I wing. The rooms pictured are the Queen’s gallery, bedchamber and oratory, and the breathtakingly stunning Studiolo. 
More to follow!

Le Château du Clos Lucé is situated just 400 meters from the Royal Castle of Amboise. It’s where Leonardo da Vinci lived and worked for the last few years of his life. 
I absolutely loved exploring the house, especially the three rooms pictured above, which comprise his actual workshops! Of course, they have been restored, but they do give a vivid idea of what an artist’s studio would have looked like at this time. 
Right up until his death on 2 May 1519, Leonardo da Vinci worked on important commissions in this very space. Absolutely mind blowing!

Some pics from my visit to the beautiful Château de Chaumont in France. Catherine de Medici is said to have entertained astronomers such as Nostradamus within its walls.
Following the death of her husband, Henri II, Catherine forced his mistress, Diane de Poitiers, to exchange the Château de Chenonceau (which Henri had gifted her) for the Château de Chaumont. 
Having visited both, I can understand why!

I absolutely love visiting cathedrals. I find it so moving to sit quietly and think about all the different people who over the centuries have sought sanctuary, healing and comfort within their ancient walls. 
Pictured is the glorious Reims Cathedral, where 25 French kings have been crowned, including Francis I in 1515.
My obsession with cathedrals continues! Today’s travels took me to the awe-inspiring Cologne Cathedral in Germany, the tallest twin-spired church in the world. Absolutely astounding!

Some pics from my visit to the wonderful Städel Museum in Frankfurt. I was absolutely blown away by their extensive collection of old masters, including works by Hans Holbein (Elder & Younger), Albrecht Durer, Lucas Cranach, Cornelis de Vos, Rembrandt and Botticelli, to name just a handful.
It was the perfect way to start the last day of our European adventure!

Some pics from my visit to the picturesque Château d'Amboise in the Loire Valley, France. It’s situated on top of a high plateau overlooking the Loire and is a must-see for anyone wishing to follow in the footsteps of a young Anne Boleyn.
The future Tudor queen spent a significant amount of time at Amboise while in service to Queen Claude. Undoubtedly, someone as perceptive and astute as Anne learnt a lot from observing her mistress and the other powerful women who frequented the court, including Louise of Savoy and her daughter Marguerite.
Within the walls of this favoured royal residence, Anne would also rub shoulders with visionaries like Leonardo da Vinci and be exposed to the ideas of French reformist writers and poets such as Clément Marot and Jacques Lefèvre d'Étaples.
While only a small section of the once sprawling palace complex survives, it’s most definitely worth a visit.

Thornbury Castle in South Gloucestershire is the only Tudor castle to be opened as a luxury hotel and as such offers guests the unique opportunity of staying in rooms where royalty and nobility slept hundreds of years ago.
In August 1535, Henry VIII and Anne Boleyn stayed at Thornbury. The king slept in what is now known as ‘The Duke’s Bedchamber’ and you can sleep there too! Staying at the castle is a truly unique and wonderful experience.

I have a real treasure to share with you today, a photo of Hever Castle taken in 1857!
Pictured on the right are the Tudor stables, sadly no longer extant. This 2-storey building housed the stables on the ground floor, a large communal hall with a crown post roof, and an outer staircase which led to an open gallery and five additional bed chambers on the first floor.
It's a building that would have been in constant use by the Boleyns, especially considering their penchant for hunting and riding.
Unfortunately, it was dismantled by Captain Guy Sebright who leased the castle in 1895 from the Meade Waldo family. Captain Sebright and his wife Olive were the last tenants of Hever Castle. 
Also visible on the left is the original guard house, where visitors would have been questioned before being permitted to enter the grounds.
A huge thank you to the wonderful @drowenemmerson for allowing me to share this photo with you.

The Château du Clos Lucé in Amboise, France, was home to Leonardo da Vinci for the last three years of his life. It was in this very bedchamber that Leonardo penned his will on 23 April 1519, bequeathing his manuscripts, sketchbooks and sketches to his favourite apprentice, Francesco Melzi. Legend has it that Francis I was by da Vinci’s bedside when he took his final breath on 2 May 1519.
 
“As a well spent day brings contented sleep, so a well spent life brings a peaceful death.”

The Parish Church of St John the Baptist in Cirencester is home to this stunning silver gilt cup and cover, known as the ‘Boleyn Cup’ since the 19th century. 
It was made in London in 1535 and measures just over 31 cm in height. The fluted cover rises to a stem surmounted by Queen Anne Boleyn’s falcon badge. 
According to tradition, Elizabeth I gave the cup to Dr Richard Master, one of her physicians, and he or one of his descendants gave it to the church. It’s a truly beautiful piece!

Worcester Cathedral is home to the tomb of Henry VII’s eldest son, Arthur, who died aged just 15 in 1502. His tomb is enclosed by a magnificent chantry chapel built by masons from Westminster Abbey. 
Had Arthur lived, he would have succeeded his father as King of England. Instead, Arthur’s younger brother, Henry, ascended the throne following Henry VII’s death in 1509.

Some pics from my visit to Stokesay Castle in Shropshire. This stunning moated medieval manor house was constructed at the end of the 13th century by Laurence of Ludlow. The great hall and solar, with its oak panelling and beautifully carved overmantel, were definite highlights.

Some pics from my visit to Blickling Hall in Norfolk. The Jacobean house was built on the footprint of a Tudor house once home to the Boleyn family. It’s widely believed to have been the birthplace of Mary and Anne Boleyn. 
Just how much of the Boleyn home Sir Henry Hobart kept and incorporated into his red-brick mansion is currently the subject of investigation.

St Margaret’s Church in Tivetshall is home to a remarkable treasure, a late fifteenth-century roodscreen with its original tympanum above.
Prior to the Reformation, the boards were probably decorated with a Crucifixion scene. However, in 1587 they were painted over with the royal arms of Elizabeth I, flanked by the lion and the dragon. Below the royal arms we find the inscription, ‘God Save Our Quene Elizabeth’ and ‘Let every sowle submit hym selfe unto the authority of the hyer powers, for there is no power but of God, the powers that be are ordayned by God’. Further below are the Ten Commandments.
The design also includes the symbols of Elizabeth’s predecessors, Henry VII, Henry VIII, Edward VI and Mary I.
Thrillingly, Anne Boleyn’s falcon badge is featured very prominently below her daughter’s arms – proof that Elizabeth very openly honoured her mother’s memory.

@kateemccaffreyhistorian’s fascinating research has shown that both Katherine and Anne owned a copy of the same book of hours printed in Paris in 1527, although Anne Boleyn’s is of better quality and more richly decorated.
You can see both these stunning books at @hever_castle. The exhibition ‘Catherine & Anne: Queens, Rivals, Mothers’ runs until 10 November 2023, but please note that Katherine’s book of hours will only be on display until 4 June 2023.

Explore St Andrew’s Church in Blickling with me!
 
It’s home to an impressive collection of brasses, many to members of the Boleyn family, including (in order of appearance): Anne Boleyn, a daughter of William Boleyn and aunt of Queen Anne Boleyn, who died aged three in 1479; Isabel or Isabella Boleyn, Geoffrey Boleyn Junior’s daughter who died in c.1485; and Cecily Boleyn, Geoffrey Boleyn Senior’s sister who died in 1458.
Most moving perhaps is the brass of Anne Wood, wife of Thomas Asteley, who carries her two babies in her arms, Anne Wood’s sister was Elizabeth, Lady Boleyn, who married Sir James Boleyn. According to tradition, in 1512, Anne was visiting her sister at Blickling when she went into labour. The babies pictured in her arms indicate that she died in or soon after childbirth.
And here’s a tantalising thought for you, perhaps the 15th century baptismal font was used to baptise a newborn Anne Boleyn!
For your viewing pleasure, some of the magnificent portraits on display at Hever Castle. 😍
Latest addition to my study! I absolutely love this print of @kathrynholeman’s poignant and beautiful charcoal drawing of Anne Boleyn. ❤️

Let’s have a look around St Peter and St Paul Church in Salle, the final resting place of Geoffrey Boleyn, (died 1440), and his wife Alice Bracton. They are the great-great-grandparents of Queen Anne Boleyn.
Their fine London-made brass originally also had small figures representing their 5 sons and 4 daughters, but the inlay is sadly lost. The inscription translates to: ‘Here lie Geoffrey Boleyn, who died 25th March, 1440, and Alice his wife and their children: on whose souls may God have mercy. Amen.’ The scroll reads, in Latin, ‘God be merciful on us sinners’.
This very grand church, built in the first half of the fifteenth century, is a testament to the great wealth of the English merchant trade in this period. It has many interesting features, including other medieval brasses (one to another member of the Boleyn family – one Simon Boleyn), a fifteenth-century font with a spectacular cover, a fifteenth-century pulpit, original choir stalls with misericords, and a painted rood screen. It is well worth a visit.

An intriguing Tudor treasure!
 
Saffron Walden Museum is home to this Tudor cupboard which is said to be adorned with relief portraits of Francis Weston and his wife Anne. Francis was one of five men executed in May 1536 for alleged adultery with Queen Anne Boleyn.
 
Thank you to the museum’s curator, Carolyn Wingfield, for providing me with the following information:
 
‘This cupboard is known as a Standing or Court Cupboard. It is made of oak and would have been used for displaying and storing plates and tableware. The two carved heads are said to be portraits of its original owners, Sir Francis and Lady Ann Weston. The Weston family lived at Sutton Park, near Guildford in Surrey. It is thought that Ann received the cupboard as a wedding gift from her father-in-law, Sir Richard Weston in 1530. The carved barrel or ‘tun’ between Ann’s initials is a pun on their surname Weston.’
 
This wonderful object is on display at Saffron Walden Museum. Head to their website for visitor information.

Let’s take a stroll around the glorious Tewkesbury Abbey! The magnificent vaulted roof of the choir, with its gilded Suns of York, was installed after Edward IV’s crucial victory against the Lancastrian forces in 1471.
The church is also renowned for its medieval glass, added to its seven quire windows in the fourteenth century and among the most outstanding survivors of their kind. It’s also home to many notable monuments, including the Dispenser Tomb, and a number of splendid chantry chapels, notably The Warwick or Beauchamp Chantry. The latter was erected in about 1430 by Isabella, Countess of Warwick, as a memorial for herself and her two husbands.
The remains of George, Duke of Clarence, and his wife Isabel, daughter of the infamous “Kingmaker”, are also said to be buried within Tewkesbury’s ancient walls.

In late July 1535, Henry VIII and Anne Boleyn visited Tewkesbury Abbey as part of their royal progress. It’s likely that they stayed in the abbot’s house, situated near the west front of the church within the abbey precincts, as it had been recently rebuilt and was the only building grand enough to host royal guests.
Although most of the claustral buildings were destroyed after the Dissolution, the abbot’s lodging was retained and forms part of what is now Abbey House. The stunning oriel window was built in 1509, the year of Henry VIII’s accession.
The abbot’s residence was located near the main abbey gateway, which still stands today. The Landmark Trust took over the lease of the ancient gatehouse in 1986 and rent it out as holiday accommodation. It’s the perfect historic base for exploring Tewkesbury and the surrounding area!

Let’s have a little wander around the magnificent Gloucester Cathedral!
When Henry VIII and Anne Boleyn arrived in Gloucester on 31st July 1535, they were greeted by the abbot and his brethren in the porch of the abbey. The royal couple dismounted their horses and knelt down on cushions provided for their comfort. They ‘kissed the cross with great reverence’, before processing to the high altar and then onto their lodgings.
Today you can stand in the south porch of the cathedral where Abbot Parker greeted his monarchs and imagine the great pomp and ceremony that accompanied their arrival.

Anne was anointed in this magnificent Coronation Chair, which has been used in coronation ceremonies since 1308. It would have been positioned on the Cosmati pavement facing the High Altar.
Anne Boleyn is not the only Anne associated with this area of the abbey. On the south side of the High Altar is the tomb of Anne of Cleves. The monument is adorned with carvings showing her initials AC with a crown, lions' heads and skulls and crossed bones. The inscription on the back, added in the 1970s, is visible from the south transept.

Hever Castle’s brilliant curatorial team has found Thomas Cromwell’s book of hours! This is the very same book seen in his famous portrait by Hans Holbein.
 
In 2021, @kateemccaffreyhistorian’s  groundbreaking research revealed that Katherine of Aragon and Anne Boleyn had copies of the same prayer book printed in 1527 by the prolific French printer, Germain Hardouyn. Cromwell’s book of hours is from this same batch! His book also retains its original silver-gilt and bejewelled binding.

Dr Emmerson is a social and cultural historian, the author of four books, and an expert contributor to a number of television documentaries. Dr Emmerson works as Castle Historian and Assistant Curator at the stunning Hever Castle in Kent where he has co-curated three exhibitions.

This is the magnificent tomb of Margaret Douglas, Countess of Lennox. She was the daughter of Margaret Tudor and her second husband Archibald Douglas, 6th Earl of Angus, and consequently the granddaughter of Henry VII and Elizabeth of York. 
Margaret died on 9 March 1578 and was buried in the south aisle of Henry VII’s chapel in Westminster Abbey, in a grave that she shares with her son Charles. He, like all of Margaret’s eight children, predeceased her.
Margaret’s eldest surviving son Henry, Lord Darnley, married Mary, Queen of Scots, and was murdered in 1567. Her grandson, James VI of Scotland, was Elizabeth I’s successor and became James I of England.

Petrus and a number of his children, including Antonietta, suffered from hypertrichosis, a rare congenital illness which left them covered in hair.

Valerie Schutte is a historian who specialises in books dedicated to Tudor queens. She is editing a special issue cluster of the Royal Studies Journal to be published in December on Tudor royal sexualities. Another little peek inside the beautiful Saint Calais Chapel that I mentioned in my previous post. Louis XII and Anne of Brittany worshipped privately in this chapel when they were in residence at the Royal Château of Blois.

Joining the speaker lineup for #365dayswiththetudorqueens are @sandravasolibooks and @david_lee_historian93! They’ll be delivering a fascinating lecture exploring how European noblewomen influenced the Tudor queens.
 
Sandra Vasoli is a researcher, writer, and historical novelist, with an avid interest in England's Tudor era, and the Italian Renaissance.  She has dedicated time and effort in unraveling the mysterious origin and provenance of what is often known as the Tower Letter, the much-discussed document held in the British Library which many think was authored by Anne Boleyn while she awaited execution in the Tower of London. Sandra is widely recognized as an authority on the subject. She has also visited the Vatican Library on several occasions, and has twice been permitted to closely examine the love letters Henry VIII wrote to Anne Boleyn. She has written articles about these and other subjects, has been a guest speaker on numerous podcasts, and has provided lectures for the 365 Days With Anne Boleyn program. Sandra's books include Anne Boleyn's Letter From the Tower, The New Edition; Pursuing A Masterpiece, a novel about a lost portrait of Anne and Henry; and Truth Endures: Anne Boleyn's Memoirs, which will be published in September 2023 by GreyLondon Press. 
 
David Lee is an Irish historian who specializes in women's history. He graduated from Maynooth University with a MA in Irish History. Located before the high altar in the chancel of the Collegiate Church of St Mary in Warwick is the magnificent tomb of Thomas Beauchamp, Earl of Warwick, and his wife Katherine Mortimer, Countess of Warwick. This is the studiolo, also known as the ‘Queen’s Study’, at the Château de Blois. It’s said to be the only remaining royal study from the French Renaissance. Francis I had it fitted out prior to 1520, but as it was later part of Catherine de’ Medici’s apartments, it’s adorned with her emblems.
The study is decorated with 180 polychromed panels, many of which conceal cabinets within. In fashion from the 1560s onwards, curiosity cabinets were hugely popular with royalty and the nobility. According to Samuel Quiccheberg, who in 1565 published the first treatise on collecting and museums, their contents fell under categories like ‘artificialia, man-made antiquities and artworks; naturalia, plants, animals, and other items from nature; scientifica, scientific instruments; exotica, objects from distant lands; and mirabilia, a bucket term for other marvels that spark wonder.’

Whitehall Palace, formerly York Place, bore witness to many key moments in Tudor history. If you’re interested in the story of Anne Boleyn, it’s where she made her first recorded appearance at the English court. It was also the setting for Anne’s marriage to Henry VIII, which took place in January 1533, and for the elaborate ceremonies that followed Anne’s coronation.
Anne and Henry actually worked together to redesign and beautify the palace following Cardinal Wolsey’s fall from favour. Simon Thurley asserts that Whitehall was ‘conceived as much by Anne as it was by Henry’. Sadly, nothing survives above ground of the Tudor palace. However, I’m still very much looking forward to reading more about its history!

This is another one of my favourite portraits of Elizabeth I. It was painted in c.1546 when she was around 13 years old. By this time, the Tudor princess was back in the line of succession, although technically still illegitimate. However, the richness of the fabric of her dress and her jewellery points to her royal birth.
Her undersleeves and the triangular forepart at the front of her skirt are made from cloth-of-silver tissued with gold. It was exclusively reserved for the king and his immediate family. When you get up close to the painting, you can also see that Elizabeth’s crimson silk gown is woven with precious metal threads. It’s a truly dazzling painting!
It’s currently on display in The Queen’s Gallery at Buckingham Palace as part of the ‘Holbein at the Tudor Court’ exhibition.

This wonderful painting of Henry VII and Elizabeth of York kneeling with their children is currently on display at The Queen’s Gallery, Buckingham Palace, as part of the Holbein at the Tudor Court exhibition.
It was painted by an unknown artist of the Flemish School and dates from c. 1503-9. In the top half of the painting, we see St George attacking the dragon before Princess Cleodolinde. In the foreground, Henry and Elizabeth are united by an angel and their children are shown to either side. Of the sons, only Prince Henry, the future Henry VIII, was alive at the time the painting was made. Of the princesses, Margaret and Mary were also alive, but their mother Elizabeth of York was not. She died in 1503 following the birth of Princess Katherine who only lived a short time. It’s an absolutely fascinating painting replete with an abundance of symbolism.

In my illustrated lecture, we’ll travel back to the summer of 1578 and follow in the footsteps of Elizabeth I as she journeys from Havering Palace to East Anglia. The lecture will begin with an introduction to Elizabethan progresses, before turning to look more closely at the route taken by the queen in 1578 and the people who hosted the royal entourage. We’ll travel with the queen and court through Essex, Hertfordshire, Suffolk, Norfolk and Cambridgeshire, briefly exploring the events that took place along the way, including the queen’s visit to Norwich Cathedral – the final resting place of her Boleyn ancestors. We’ll also consider why this journey was made and discuss the political and religious context of the time.
 
The ticket price includes access to 7 pre-recorded lectures and one live Zoom discussion with myself and @drowenemmerson. Participants will also be entered into a special giveaway, have access to all recordings for two months, and be able to download the lectures for private use only. 
 
I hope you’ll consider joining us!
For details and to reserve your place, click on the link in my profile.

Exeter Cathedral is home to the tomb of Bishop Hugh Oldman, who died on 25 June 1519. The chapel was heavily defaced in the early years of the Reformation. The statues on the stone altar and in the niches of the ornate screen were decapitated – a poignant reminder of the violence enacted in the name of religion. While this damage has not been repaired, Oldman’s effigy has been repainted many times over the centuries.

Because every Tudor bookshelf needs a touch of colour, it is a delight to announce the upcoming publication of ‘Colouring History: The Ultimate Tudor Colouring Book’. This new collection of historically-based illustrations will be published on the 25th of January this year. Natalie Grueninger, author and podcast host of Talking Tudors, and illustrator Kathryn Holeman have included favorites from their out-of-print ‘Tudor Queens and Consorts’ plus 20 NEW drawings featuring more players and places from the Tudor court. Excitingly, you can now pre-order this book from many countries around the world on Amazon Prime! 

Add your colouring style to illustrations of Henry VIII, Katherine of Aragon, Anne Boleyn, Jane Seymour, Anne of Cleves, Catherine Howard, Kateryn Parr, Thomas Cromwell, Thomas More, Edward VI, Lady Jane Grey, Mary I, Elizabeth I, and Mary Stuart, Queen of Scots. Let your colour pencils lead you to the lost palaces of Richmond and Nonsuch and the grand views of Hever Castle and Hampton Court Palace. On each facing page is a caption that includes more information about the original artwork or structure that inspired each drawing.

One of the highlights of my last visit to England was getting to see Thomas Cromwell’s book of hours. This is the very same book seen in his famous portrait by Hans Holbein! Hever Castle’s brilliant curatorial team (@ali_palmer1979 @kateemccaffreyhistorian @drowenemmerson) made the astounding discovery last year.
 
In 2021, Kate McCaffrey’s groundbreaking research revealed that Katherine of Aragon and Anne Boleyn had copies of the same prayer book printed in 1527 by the prolific French printer, Germain Hardouyn. Cromwell’s book of hours is from this same batch! His book also retains its original silver-gilt and bejewelled binding.
 
It was amazing to see it in the flesh, especially alongside Anne Boleyn’s prayer book.

‘A Weekend with Elizabeth I’ is a 2-day online event exploring the life of this iconic Tudor queen. The lectures will cover various aspects of Elizabeth’s life and reign, including her love of fashion. The brilliant Professor Maria Hayward’s lecture is entitled ‘Dressing like a Queen: Elizabeth I's Wardrobe and her Fashion Preferences’.
 
“As the daughter of Henry VIII and the sister of Mary I, Elizabeth I would have seen how they both used clothing to assert their position as sovereign. This talk explores how she built on their examples to fashion her own distinct style which combined elements of tradition with the new fashions that emerged during the second half of the sixteenth century.”

Another ‘pinch me’ moment from my recent trip to England was getting to see the back of the astronomical clock at Hampton Court Palace. Yes, the back! The clock was designed by Henry VIII’s astrologer, Nicolaus Kratzer, and constructed in 1540 by Nicholas Oursian. It tells the time, day, month, position of the sun and phase of the moon and is an incredible feat of Tudor engineering. Importantly, it also tells the time of the tides, useful for those busy courtiers planning trips to London.
I’m indebted to @historic_leigh_speaking and @anneboleynsociety for making this incredible experience possible. It was also wonderful to share this moment with the wonderful @sandravasolibooks.

Let’s have a wander around the romantic ruins of Berry Pomeroy Castle in Devon. It was built in the late 15th century by the Pomeroy family and then later extended by the Seymour family. In 1547, Edward Seymour, the then Lord Protector, purchased the castle. Following his execution, it became the residence of his eldest son, Sir Edward Seymour. He and his descendants worked on transforming the castle into a fashionable country house. Their grand plans, however, were never fully realised and the castle was abandoned in the seventeenth century.

‘A Weekend with Elizabeth I’ is a 2-day online event exploring various aspects of the life and reign of Elizabeth I, including her dramatic early years. The wonderful @historian_nicola will present a lecture entitled ‘Young Elizabeth: Princess. Prisoner. Queen.’ You don’t want to miss this!
 
“Elizabeth I is one of England's most famous monarchs, whose story as the ‘Virgin Queen’ is well known. But queenship was by no means a certain path for Henry VIII’s younger daughter, who spent the majority of her early years as a girl with an uncertain future.

Before she was three years old Elizabeth had been both a princess and then a bastard following the brutal execution of her mother, Anne Boleyn. After losing several stepmothers and then her father, the teenage Elizabeth was confronted with the predatory attentions of Sir Thomas Seymour. The result was devastating, causing a heartbreaking rift with her beloved stepmother Katherine Parr.

Elizabeth was placed in further jeopardy when she was implicated in the Wyatt Rebellion of 1554 – a plot to topple her half-sister, Mary, from her throne. Imprisoned in the Tower of London where her mother had lost her life, under intense pressure and interrogation Elizabeth adamantly protested her innocence. Though she was eventually liberated, she spent the remainder of Mary’s reign under a dark cloud. On 17 November 1558, however, the uncertainty of Elizabeth’s future came to an end when she succeeded to the throne at the age of twenty-five. Join Dr Tallis as she guides us through the heart racing story of Elizabeth’s youth.”

These 13 steps lead to the room known as ‘Anne Boleyn’s Bedroom’ at Hever Castle. This was the first of the Boleyn family’s private suite of rooms and probably served as an antechamber to the family’s Great Chamber next door.

Another one of the highlights of my last visit to England was getting to see the upper chamber of the Bell Tower at the Tower of London, where the poet Thomas Wyatt was imprisoned in May 1536. It was from this very room that Wyatt witnessed the executions of George Boleyn, Henry Norris, William Brereton, Francis Weston and Mark Smeaton on Tower Hill.
In his poem, Innocentia Veritas Viat Fides Circumdederunt me, he reflects on the reversal of fortune that so often afflicts those who draw too close to the throne. The third and fourth stanzas speak for themselves:
 
These bloody days have broken my heart.
My lust, my youth did them depart,
And blind desire of estate.
Who hastes to climb seeks to revert.
Of truth, circa Regna tonat. [it thunders around the throne]
 
The bell tower showed me such a sight
That in my head sticks day and night.
There did I learn out of a grate,
For all favour, glory, or might,
That yet, circa Regna tonat.
 
It was utterly chilling to inhabit this space and imagine Wyatt standing at the window watching the unspeakable horrors unfolding on Tower Hill. It’s little wonder his heart broke.
A huge thank you to my brilliant buddy @drowenemmerson for accompanying me and to the wonderful @tracy.borman and @alfredrjhawkins_history for making this very special visit possible.
 
PS. If you’re wondering about the picture of Bishop Fisher, he was also imprisoned in this chamber. It’s been suggested that Princess Elizabeth was too, although this has been disputed.

In the sixteenth century, these stairs, known today as the Queen’s stairs, were the main river entrance for royalty arriving at the Tower of London. In 1533, Queen Anne Boleyn arrived here by boat to prepare for her coronation celebrations. Less than three years later she would climb these stairs once again, but this time on her way to her incarceration and execution. Once on the wharf, she crossed the drawbridge and entered the Byward Postern gate. From there, it was just a short walk to the entrance of the royal lodgings, which are now lost but once stood in the south-east corner of the Tower, where she would spend her imprisonment.

Some have interpreted Anne Boleyn’s motto to be evidence of her arrogance. But in the sixteenth century, the word happy usually meant fortunate or lucky. In light of this, Anne’s motto, ‘The Most Happy’, rather than being haughty or egotistical, is a humble acknowledgement of her privileged position. She was essentially ‘the most lucky’ because Henry had raised her to be his queen.
